    "updated_at": "2015-11-10T23:27:08Z",
    "body": "Laying aside type-safety, memory safety and so on and speaking strictly of the build system and modules, what am I winning in exchange? In C++ I can do `g++ -o app main.cpp xml_usecase.cpp -lexpat` and \"up-arrow\" is my makefile. The `-lexpat` is a wart on C++, right? When I start to add other things to my app like HTTP further `-l` options come along and I have to use `pkg-config` even if I'm using a makefile. In a clean-sheet design that sort of information could be embedded in xml_usecase.rs instead of having to be remembered in command history or a build script. In rust it seems like I have to work harder at an earlier stage, and the idea that  xml_usecase.rs provides an abstraction is not attained as compensation if I have to maintain a list of crate names in my root `.rs` file.  \n",
